The grammar is extremely permissive: every terminal occurring in the string (`t1, t2, t6, t8, t13, t15, t23, t36`) can be produced by at least one non-terminal (e.g. NT3→t1, NT24→t2/​t8, NT0/NT1→t6, NT41→t13/​t36, NT44→t15, NT5/NT32→t23).  
Moreover, these non-terminals are tied together through dozens of binary rules that form mutually recursive cycles (for instance NT32 → NT36 NT27 while NT36 → NT23 NT32, NT24 → NT15 NT34 with NT34 → NT21 NT46 where NT46 eventually reaches back to NT24, and so on). Because of these cycles, any of the listed non-terminals can grow to an arbitrary sequence of other non-terminals before finally yielding a terminal, and concatenations of such sequences can be built up indefinitely.  

The start symbol S launches two such recursive sub-derivations (`S → NT48 NT2`, `S → NT24 NT24`, or `S → NT12 NT20`). Each branch, via the mutual recursion just described, can expand to any finite sequence over the terminal alphabet. Therefore S can generate every finite string composed of the eight terminals in the grammar, including the 43-token string supplied.

Consequently the given string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes
